            </ns0:div>
            <ns0:div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <ns0:p>The epitaph consists of a single name in the genitive, as with the majority of the epitaphs attested from this necropolis. The name <ns0:ref target="http://www.lgpn.ox.ac.uk/name/%E1%BC%88%CE%B8%CE%AC%CE%BD%CE%B9%CF%80%CF%80%CE%BF%CF%82">&#7944;&#952;&#940;&#957;&#953;&#960;&#960;&#959;&#962;</ns0:ref> is not a common one, with only one other known (probably) Sicilian instance (IG II/III (2nd edn) 10293: &#7965;&#961;&#956;&#969;&#957; | &#7944;&#952;&#945;&#957;&#943;&#960;&#960;&#959;&#965; | &#931;&#953;&#954;&#949;&#955;&#8056;&#962; | &#7936;&#960;&#8056; &#932;&#965;&#957;&#948;&#945;&#961;&#943;&#948;&#959;&#962;, a funerary inscription from Athens of the imperial period.</ns0:p>
            </ns0:div>
